contends that mental illness is better characterized in terms of struggle than symptoms and that culture is central to all aspects of mental illness from onset to recovery. Her analysis refashions the boundaries between the ordinary and the extraordinary, the routine and the extreme, and the healthy and the pathological. This book asserts that the study of mental illness is indispensable to the anthropological understanding of culture and experience, and reciprocally that understanding culture and experience is critical to the study of mental illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnopsychology. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aMental illnessvCross-cultural studies. 0aMental illnessxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  adehumanization of mental illness.  adisability studies.  adivergent mental states.  aethnopsychology.  afamily impact of mental illness.  amadness.  amarginalization of mentally ill.  amedical anthropology.  amental health care.  amental health in the us.  amental health.  amental illness in the us.  amental illness.  apsychology.  apsychosis.  arecovery from mental illness.  aschizophrenia.  astudy of mental illness.  atrauma studies.  atrauma.  aviolence and trauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028709940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096222440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962224/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY